article.headline: Laimbeer tossed after arguing calls in first half
article.linkText: Technical knockout: Laimbeer ejected as Shock fall big
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- In a game that featured five
technicals and the ejection of Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer, Nicole
Powell scored 17 points to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to an 80-63
win over the Shock on Friday night.

Laimbeer was ejected for arguing a call with 3:49 left in the
first half. He received a pair of technicals for protesting what he
thought was a foul by a Sacramento player in front of the Shock
bench.

"We're not playing hard enough at all," said Laimbeer, whose
team has lost five of its last six games. "We're out there
floating around and it's costing us."

Yolanda Griffith scored 15 points and reserve Rebekkah Brunson
had a career-high 14 for the Western Conference-leading Monarchs
(11-4).

DeMya Walker, who averages a team-leading 14.8 points for
Sacramento, left the game with a right knee injury early in the
second half. Walker finished with 10 points on 5-of-7 shooting.

"We haven't done an MRI or an X-ray, but the impression is that
she got hit on the knee brace and it hurt," said Sacramento coach
John Whisenant. "It is the same knee she strained about two weeks
ago."

With her third assist of the game, Ticha Penicheiro picked up
the 1,500th of her career. She finished with 10 points and six
assists for the Monarchs.

Newcomer Plenette Pierson, acquired by Detroit (6-6) in a trade
Wednesday with the Phoenix Mercury, had 22 points and Deanna Nolan
added 14 for the Shock.

"Coming in here, I wanted to mesh with the girls as best as
possible," said Pierson, who made 8-of-13 shots. "I was going to
do what was asked of me. And I was asked to be aggressive and go to
the basket and the girls helped me out with that."

Detroit was lethargic from the opening tip, committing 15
turnovers in the first half. But the Shock shot 10-of-20 from the
floor to trail just 38-31 at the break. They finished with 22
turnovers.

Laimbeer liked what he saw from Pierson.

"We're looking for some scoring from the three position and
it's clear that she can do that," he said. "We just need people
to match her intensity now."

The Monarchs never relinquished the lead, and Detroit trailed by
as many as 14 points midway through the second half.

Whisenant got the first technical with 9:18 in the first half
for arguing with an official. Detroit's Cheryl Ford, who had eight
points and 12 rebounds, received a technical with 18:08 left in the
second half. Shock assistant coach Rick Mahorn got a technical in
the final minute.

Laimbeer's early exit marked the third time he has been ejected
in four seasons as coach.
